1 Introduction

This tutorial instructs on how to use a workflow for a typical but simple Git use case. This includes making limited use of GitHub.

2 Learning Objectives

After completing this tutorial, you should be able to:

  1. Create a private repository (repo) on GitHub.

  2. Clone the repo to your computer, i.e.Â create a local repo.

  3. Add a tiny demo R script to the repo.

  4. Stage the changes.

  5. Create a commit.

  6. Push the commit to the remote repo, i.e.Â the GitHub from where you cloned the repo.

5 Clone Repo

5.1 Clone 1

Note

This first attempt to clone the repo from the remote (i.e.Â GitHub) to a local repo (i.e.Â on your computerâs disk drive) will fail. See below for the reason.

Open a Command Prompt window and enter the git clone command as shown below.

The highlighted portion of the command is the name of the repo.

Since the repo is private, the clone process prompts to have you enter the GitHub credentials for the skip123paschall GitHub account. DO NOT ENTER THE CREDENTIALS. Instead click on the X to close this window.

Note

Enter credentials as prompted in the preceding screenshot will result in your GitHub credentials being stored in the Windows Credential Manager (WCM). Using WCM can be appropriate in some circumstance, but it can introduce complications that are avoided in this tutorial. Instead, later in this tutorial, youâll be instructed to take a different, simpler, approach to clone a private GitHub repo where you are the owner of the GitHub account.

After you click X to close the dialogue window shown above, youâll see a command line prompt asking for your GitHub user name. Again, DO NOT ENTER your GitHub user name. Instead close the Command Prompt window.

5.2 Clone 2

Note

This attempt to clone repo Git_1st_time will work because a PAT will be put into the URL for the remote (i.e.Â GitHub) repo.

Open another Command Prompt window and re-enter the git clone command, but this time the URL will contain the Personal Access Token (PAT) that you created when your GitHub account was created in the GitHub Get Started tutorial.

The PAT is highlighted in the screenshot below. Notice the @ sign needs to be added before the github.com part.

Note

Be aware the git clone command shown above is simple is that it allows authentication to GitHub because the PAT is passed directly in the URL. There is a security risk that the PAT could be intercepted by someone who is âsniffingâ your internet transmission. Practically speaking, the risk is low especially in a training/tutorial situation. In a a professional / production work environment, your security team will require and advise on GitHub authentication techniques that are more secure.

The git clone command shown in the preceding screenshot will succeed. The screenshot below shows some information regarding the successful clone.

The clone process created a folder named âGit_1st_timeâ within the Documents folder.

The Git_1st_time folder contains the .gitignore and README files that were created by GitHub when the repo was created using GitHub.

The .gitignore file is a hidden file. The .gitignore file identifies files and folders within the project that will not be tracked by Git. Therefore, when you do a push to send data to GitHub these ignored files and folders will not be sent.

A hidden .git folder was also created. This .git folder actually holds the Git local repo.

One of the files in the .git folder is the config file. Specifically, this file is referred to as the local Git config file and items in this file will override items in the Global config file, which overrides items in the System config file.

Using Notepad++, examine the contents of the Git local config file.

The git clone command created an entry in the config file to identify the URL of the remote repo associated with the local Git repo. Note how the PAT is also part of the URL. Having the PAT in the URL will make it easy to push future commits to GitHub because no additional authentication is needed. However, keep in mind this local Git config file must be handled in a secure manner so your GitHub PAT is not accessed by another person.

6.5 Stage R script

Note

Before staging the R script, this tutorial needs to provide information about several key Git concepts. So, below are several narratives that introduce these key concepts.

Note

Git workflow

A key part of the Git workflow involves the progression of files through this workflow:

Working Directory => Staging Area (Index) => Commit

An important aspect of a Git repository (repo) is that itâs the accumulation of all commits performed on the repo.

Note

Working Directory - general concepts

Good news: you can esily see the files and folders that are in working directory.

What you see in the RStudio Files tab panel or when looking at your project using File Explorer is what Git calls the âWorking Directoryâ. To you, these are the files and folders that make up the current version of your project. You do all the typical things with the files and folder in the working directory just as if you were not using Git with your project, i.e.Â change existing files, add files and delete files.

But, since your project is âunder Git version controlâ then Git monitors the files and folders in your projectâs working directory. When you do a git status, Git is able to report about changes to the working directory. At this point in the tutorial youâve recently added a new file (code_challenge.r) to the working directory. Git has detected this new file. However, git status says the R script is an âUntracked fileâ. One way to envision the situation is to say that code_challeng.r is in the project, but not yet âofficiallyâ part of the Git repo.

The way to make Git âofficiallyâ recognize code_challenge.r as being part of the repo is to run git add, which puts the file into the Git staging area (also called the Git index).

Note

Staging Area (Index)

Bad news: âStaging Areaâ and âIndexâ pretty much mean the same thing in Git. Having two names for the same thing often causes confusion for new Git users. Mostly in this tutorial, Iâll say staging area instead of index. One reason for my preference of say âstaging areaâ is that most people will often say something like, âthe code has been tested, so now letâs stage the code file(s)â.

Bad news: after doing git add, you must run git status or git ls-files to see the files and folders that are in the staging area.

Use the git add . command to add the code_challenge.r file to the Git staging area (a.k.a. index). The code below uses a . after add. Using the period is like a wildcard. The period instructs Git to add all new files and folders to the staging area. Typically, itâs appropriate to just use the period. However, if you want to stage a single file then you could code âgit add code_challenge.râ. In the case of this tutorial it would be the same as coding âgit add .â.

Once code_challenge.r has been staged then Git will now be tracking any future changes to this file. Another way of stating this is to say that âcode_challenge.râ is now under version control.

The screenshot below also shows the result of again running git status after the git add. This time the status is reporting the code_challenge.r file is ready to be committed. When files are in the staging area then Git suggests the next step is to run git commit (this will be discussed next).

6.6 Create commit

Run the git commit command in order to create a commit that contains all the files and folders that are in the Git staging area. Once a commit is created the staging area is cleared, i.e.Â no longer contains any files or folders.

Note

Again, the way people discuss using Git can vary and cause confusion.

People sometimes so âdo a commitâ, âcommit the changesâ, or âperform a commitâ. They all mean the same thing. Regardless, whatâs actually happening is that a commit is being created.

Commits are an essential part of using Git. One way of envisioning a commit is to think of it as a snapshot of a set of file and folder changes that youâve made to your repo at a given point of time. If in the future youâve made additional changes to a file that was parat of an earlier commit then you can use Git commands to retrieve the state of that file as it was at the point of the earlier commit. The Git term ârevertâ is associated with for this âtraveling back in timeâ to obtain an earlier version of a file that was included in a commit.

For this tutorial, there is just one file in the staging area so the commit consists of just a single file, i.e.Â code_challenge.r.

Note

Remove file from staging area before commit.

If you put a file into the staging area (i.e.Â by doing a âgit addâ) then that action can easily be undone. What that means is that you can remove a single item or all items from the staging area by doing a git restore. Remember though, git restore must be done before doing git commit.

Reverting a commit

As mentioned earlier, there are ways to reverse (the term is revert) a commit but itâs more complicated and will be discussed in a later tutorial. For now, just make sure that before creating a commit that youâre happy with the files and folders that are in the staging area.

Since a commit is a permanent item in a repo and since you may want to go back and retrieve a file that was in a commit done sometime in the (recent or far) past then itâs important to have a description of the changes that were part of a commit. For this reason, Git requires that a message be created when you do a commit. It can be a short message or a long one. The screenshot below shows using the -m flag to created a short message. If the -m flag is omitted then when the commit command is executed a text editor will open where you can create a long commit message. When you area searching through a list of past commits, you can see your commit messages. This could help you to identify a specific commit if youâre seeking to revert back to an earlier version of a specific file.

The screenshot below also shows the results of git status after the commit has been created.

The âOn branch mainâ line indicates that your working directory reflects whatâs on the branch of your repo that is named âmainâ. You have not created any other branches as part of this tutorial.

The line that says, âYour branch is ahead of âorigin/mainâ by 1 commit.â uses the word âoriginâ. By default Git uses âoriginâ as a shorthand way of referring to the URL for the remote (GitHub in this case) repository that corresponds to your local Git repo (thatâs on your computerâs hard drive). The âis ahead ofâ part of the message indicates youâve created a commit on your local repo and that commit is not yet in the remote repo. The message finally suggests that you do âgit pushâ to publish your local commitsâ. Doing git push is a way to synchronize your local and remote Git repositories. Doing git push is discussed next.

Finally the line ânothing to commit, working tree cleanâ is saying the staging area is empty and also there are not any un-staged changes in the working directory.

6.7 Do push

You can create a single commit and then push that commit to your remote repo. You can also create multiple commits (for example three commits) and then push all three commits to the remote repo in conjunction with a single push.

At this point in this tutorial, just one commit has been created and it will now be pushed to the remote repo.

The push command in the screenshot below uses origin, which (recall) is shorthand for the URL of the remote repo. See the project-level config file for details of the origin.

The push command seen below also uses main, which (recall) is the name of the Git branch that contains the commit being pushed to the remote repo. For this tutorial, weâve only worked with a single branch that is named âmainâ.

The line stating, âYour branch is up to date with âorigin/mainâ is saying your local and remote repositories are now synchronized.

8 Collaborate

Note

Using Git and GitHub to facilitate collaboration is beyond the scope of this tutorial. However, this brief section is included to provide a peak at whatâs possible and as a preview of information to be covered in a future tutorial.

8.1 With yourself

A prime example of using Git and GitHub to collaborate with yourself would be a situation where youâve been developing a solution on your office desktop computer but you want to continue working on it on your laptop computer while you away attending a conference.

Since, at this point in this tutorial, your local and remote repositories are synchronized then you can simply perform a git clone on your laptop. Doing so will create a local repo on your laptop that is the exact copy of the repo that is on your desktop copy.

While your at the conference, you can working on the local repo on your laptop and as needed stage and commit changes. You will need to eventually push commits created on your laptop to the remote repo.

When you return to your office, you can perform a git pull on your desktop computer to merge the changes (now on the remote repo) into your local repo. When thatâs done then you can resume working on your project using the local Git repo thatâs on your desktop computer.

9 With others

If a time comes when you want to share your project with others and possibly have them also work on your project then the remote repo located on GitHub will again the key resource that will enable collaboration.

Collaborating with others introduces many other considerations (and to some degree complexity) in using Git and GitHub. But both are well-designed to support collaboration. In future tutorials, you can learn how to convert a project from private to public so other can access it. Additional Git and GitHub features that support collaboration include (1) forking a repo that is on GitHub, (2) creating a pull request and (3) merging changes.
